<div id="review_495411066" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/495411066" />
    <a title="Connie G" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5364077-connie-g"><img alt="Connie G" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1307502493p2/5364077.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/495411066?book_show_action=true">Jan 04, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Connie G" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Connie G" href="/user/show/5364077-connie-g">Connie G</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5364077-connie-g?shelf=classic">classic</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5364077-connie-g?shelf=georgia">georgia</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5364077-connie-g?shelf=coming-of-age">coming-of-age</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5364077-connie-g?shelf=southern-lit">southern-lit</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer495411066" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer18018112872507739169">Frankie is feeling lonely, and isolated in this coming-of-age story: &quot;It happened that green and crazy summer when Frankie was twelve years old. This was the summer when for a long time she had not been a member. She belonged to no club and was a member of nothing in the world. Frankie had become an unjoined person who hung around doorways, and she was afraid.&quot; Her mother died when Frankie was born, her father is distant, and her best friend moved away. Frankie wonders if she might turn into a f</span>
  <span id="freeText18018112872507739169" style="display:none">Frankie is feeling lonely, and isolated in this coming-of-age story: "It happened that green and crazy summer when Frankie was twelve years old. This was the summer when for a long time she had not been a member. She belonged to no club and was a member of nothing in the world. Frankie had become an unjoined person who hung around doorways, and she was afraid." Her mother died when Frankie was born, her father is distant, and her best friend moved away. Frankie wonders if she might turn into a freak because she is at a gangly, awkward stage. Her wish to belong to a group is so strong that she comes up with the idea of going away with her brother and his bride after their wedding.<br /><br />The story also shows Carson McCullers' concern for other individuals that are excluded because they are different. Bernice, the African American maid, tells how difficult it is having dark skin. Frankie, who is a tomboy, wishes that people could switch back and forth from being boys to girls. Her cousin, John Henry, wants people to be "half boy and half girl."<br /><br />A small town is hard on anyone that's different, and feeling excluded. Frankie is fascinated that the soldiers have the opportunity to travel to other places. "The Member of the Wedding" is a heartbreaking coming-of-age novel, but there is hope for a more realistic Frankie by the end of the story.</span>
  <a data-text-id="18018112872507739169" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


